## North Star

**The desired outcome this brand exists to accomplish:**

Build a community around E.I. Werner as a fantasy writer and creative leader that makes the writing career financially sustainable and less lonely. The room full of people who chose to care about the things done alone for 18 years. That room has a name: The Outside Inn. Motivate people to fully commit to their own dreams through the undimmed passion of an 18-year grind with almost nothing to show for it — and give fantasy lovers, productive gamers, and writers in the trenches a front-row seat to how the work actually gets made, with real opportunities to engage and contribute along the way. So that when the books are ready, the audience is already there and already cares.

**Community is the engine. Everything else serves it.**

Notion coaching buys runway so the community can breathe. Merch is how the community wears the thing. Writing is what the community is *about* — it is the reason the room exists and the thing that makes it different from every other gaming Discord. When in doubt about any strategic decision, return to this hierarchy: does it grow the community, deepen it, or sustain the person building it? If not, deprioritize it.

**What must Evan be known for in order for that to happen:**

A fantasy author who actually builds his world in public. Someone who has been going for 18 years without external validation and is still going. A leader with earnest charisma who lifts people up around the things the world told them to downplay.

**What he must consistently do:**

Stream live, writing into gaming, three times a week. Build the ONCE mythology in public. Lock in a brand statement and then say it until the audience says it back. Be the proof of concept. Keep collaborators in the loop and send debriefs after milestones.

**What he's still learning:**

Validate before building. Lead with warmth, not clinical efficiency under pressure. The audience doesn't need to see the walls — they need to see the writer behind them. Overcome perfectionism — the beta period is for trying things, not for getting them right the first time. Build systems that are sustainable and fun, not impressive and fragile. How to be natural on camera — the first two streams proved this is a muscle, not a switch. The stiffness fades. The stride moments are the signal. Structure is the unlock — knowing where the stream is going and what comes next lets the personality relax into the format instead of white-knuckling through open space. Pre-stream checklists are not optional — YouTube settings reset between streams and will burn you every time you skip them.

