## Voice & Tone

**Warm but not soft.** The brand has teeth. The warmth is real but it comes from a place of conviction, not performance.

**Direct over diplomatic.** He says what he means. He edits for clarity, not to sand down the edges.

**Earnest without being naïve.** The passion is not ironic. The 18-year commitment is not a joke.

**Singular "you."** Always "you," never "you guys." Speaks to one person. Creates intimacy.

**Human as possible.** In an era of AI-generated content, being authentically human is the ultimate competitive advantage. Leave the silly moments in.

**Second stream reality check (Mar 4):** Showed up on no sleep again. Stream went live and immediately hit two technical issues — YouTube reset to "made for kids," chat was off. Lost waiting room viewers when the stream restarted. The freeze is shrinking. The checklist now exists. The reps are accumulating. Every stream this awkward is one fewer awkward stream ahead. The stride moments are coming more often and lasting longer. Keep showing up.

**When you explain, you lose.** This is a broadcasting law, not a suggestion. The audience that needs the explanation isn't your audience yet. The audience that gets it without the explanation already is. Never stop a stream to explain the brand architecture, the membership tiers, what the Outside Inn is, or why the prices end in sevens. Just be it. Let them catch up.

- Resume language — listing credentials without making them useful to the viewer
- Hedging — "I think maybe," "kind of," "sort of"
- Downplaying — "just a fantasy author," "just streaming," "just for fun"
- Performative humility — false modesty reads worse than honest confidence
- Clinical efficiency when warmth is what the moment calls for
- Classroom energy — Notion open with no framing reads like a lecture, not a writing session

---

## Brand Guardrails — What This Brand Is Not

**This is not a content farm.** The streams exist because they are the writing. The moment a stream feels like it is competing with the writing for time and energy, something has gone wrong.

**This is not a tips-and-tricks channel.** The ONCE mythology is not "10 worldbuilding tips." The content is the thing itself — shown in real time.

**This is not a review channel.** Other people's work is not the primary content.

**This is not a performance.** Delivery = removing everything that keeps Evan from being fully himself. The natural version is the right version.

**This is not a platform for half-baked hot takes.** The Tattoo Test applies. Would he still stand behind it in 15 years? If yes — say it loud. If not sure — hold it back.

**This is not a brand built for the algorithm.** "I am not building a brand to please the algorithm. I am building a brand that allows me to talk about writing, fantasy, and games while still being a full human."

**This is not a gaming content channel.** Gaming is community. It is not a pillar the brand is obligated to feed.

---

## Technology & Operational Advantage

Most creator brands at this stage hire contractors or agencies for ecommerce setup, streaming infrastructure, payment integration, analytics, and tooling. Outside Inn doesn't need to.

**Ecommerce & Payments:** Evan integrated 8+ payment types onto a single platform at SKIMS, architected order management across OMS/ERP/WMS, and built the middleware connecting all of it. Setting up Fourthwall, managing product feeds, pricing logic, and payment flows is execution, not learning.

**Streaming & Infrastructure:** The entire OBS/Restream stack, dual-WAN failover, battery backup architecture, and scene automation were designed and configured by Evan. No streaming consultant. No IT hire.

**HTML/OBS Overlay Capability (unlocked Mar 3–4):** Evan can now build sophisticated OBS Browser Source overlays in HTML/CSS/JS — countdown timers, animated patron rolls, dynamic scene elements — through Claude pair-programming. This is a production capability, not a one-off. The combination of technical fluency, Stream Deck automation, and HTML overlay development means OIS can build stream experiences that most creator brands spend thousands on. The patron roll, the countdown timer, the font-switching between scenes — all of this is buildable in-house, fast, and iteratively. This is a compounding advantage. Every stream will benefit from it.

**What this means in practice:** When a creative idea comes up for a stream visual, the conversation is "how do we build it in HTML" not "who do we hire." Claude and Evan have established a working pattern for this. Use it aggressively.

**Pre-Stream Checklist:** A formal pre-stream checklist has been built and saved (separate document). It is not optional. YouTube settings reset between streams. The checklist is the insurance.

**Data & Analytics:** Built Watchtower (real-time financial dashboard for SKIMS CFO), Apollo (CX platform, 94% error reduction), and Lighthouse (retail ops). Can build OIS dashboards without third-party tools.

**AI Tooling:** Uses Claude and other AI tools as production infrastructure — brand ops, content strategy, document management, overlay development. Not novelty. Production.

**Agile & Scaling:** Introduced Scrum to SKIMS from scratch, scaled team ~5→40+. Project management infrastructure exists in muscle memory.

**What this saves:** Conservative estimate — $2,000–$5,000/month in contractor costs. That's runway.

**Expert Network Validation:** Active expert on GLG, AlphaSights, Guidepoint at $399/hour. Same expertise deployed on OIS at no incremental cost.

